Cloud Simulation
CS284A Final Project Milestone Status Report
FANGPING SHI, GANG YAO, and HSIN-PEI LEE, UC Berkeley
Clouds are an important component of the visual simulation of any outdoor
scene, but the complexity of cloud formation, dynamics, and light interaction
makes cloud simulation and rendering dicult in real time. In this project,
we created a 3D cloud simulation that renders realistic clouds in Unity. We
developed three dierent cloud types (polygon mesh, geometric, and volu-
metric) using techniques such as ray-marching, parallax mapping, shader
graph, and noise texture. We then animated and simulated cloud movements
in some sample scenes.

1 POLYGON MESH CLOUD SEA
Cloud sea are made of very dense clouds, meaning it behaves very
much like oceans. By layering levels of noise onto a 2D mesh plane
we can create and tune the shape of the cloud sea.
1.1 Mesh Subdivision
To produce thousands of polygons, we apply loop subdivion that
we learned in project 2 in Blender. The original mesh is subdivided
into nearly 100,000 polygons. After that, we import the mesh into
Unity to apply further process.
Fig. 1. Subdivide the original mesh.
1.2 Shader Graph
Authoring shaders in GLSL has traditionally been the realm of peo-
ple with some programming ability. Unity Shader Graph opens up
the eld for artists and other team members by making it easy to
create shaders. We can simply connect nodes in a graph network
and see the changes instantly.
Authors address: Fangping Shi; Gang Yao; Hsin-Pei Lee, UC Berkeley.
1.3 Cloud Motion by Height Map
Using the shader graph built-in gradient noise component [gra
[n.d.]], we can generate a noise texture whose intensity at each uv
point will be mapped to the height of a given mesh vertex from the
world coordinate. For example, gure 2 shows the implementation
of unity gradient noise. We can tweak and play around with gradi-
ent noise and oset the texture relative to time to generate cloud
movement.
Fig. 2. Unity Shader Graph
1.4 Relief Parallax Mapping
To boost the detail of the clouds, we implement relief parallax map-
ping (RPM) to transform a at plane to a rough bumpy surface based
on a materials geometric properties. As shown in gure 3, parallax
mapping is implemented by displacing the texture coordinates at
a point on the rendered polygon by a function of the view angle
in tangent space (the angle relative to the surface normal) and the
value of the height map at that point. At steeper view-angles, the
texture coordinates are displaced more, giving the illusion of depth
due to parallax eects as the view changes. [lea [n.d.]]
Fig. 3. Relief Parallax Mapping Overview

1.5 Results
Figure 4 shows the polygon cloud sea rendered with and without
RPM. The left one looks more cartoonlike and it does not contain
lots of details. The right side on the other hand is more realistic
with gradient color and a bumpy surface.

to improve eciency by stepping the maximum distance forward
without hitting any surface instead of one tiny step at a time.

and estimate light transfer and shade the given pixel just like in
ray-tracing. We have dened distance functions for torus, spheres,

2.3 Constructing Cloud Object
By stacking spheres and play around a little, we managed to render
something that resembles a cloud, preferably used in "cartoon" style
movies and game. We also added soft shadow and rim lighting by
setting the pixel to a set color when the dot product between view
ray and surface normal is small enough.
We tried to animate the cloud motion by asking the spheres to move
randomly in a designated area relative to time. We also added a
buer shader to capture the pixel value from the previous frame and

3 VOLUMETRIC CLOUD
To make more realistic cloud, noise-based cloud generation com-
bined with physical based volumetric rendering is often used in
industrial level rendering.
3.1 Volumetric Rendering
In this section we will briey discuss the physical theory of the volu-
metric rendering. Volume is essentially large collections of particles.
The density of the particles is relatively low to their volume. When
photons goes through the volume, they will collide with particles,
causing the energy to be absorbed and re-emitted by the particles.
In a word, volumetric rendering is a method to statistically simulate
the behavior of light passing through a volume.

3.2 Cloud Generation
In this section we will give a brief introduction on how to generate
cloud. The basic pipeline for generating cloud can be 2 steps. First
we generate a whether map that controls where can cloud appear
and its height. Then we will add noise to the cloud to shape it. All
these steps will nally result in a 3D density map because volume
is better described as collections of density-altering particles
Fig. 12. Typical Clouds
3.2.1 Weather Map. Cloud map is a 2D texture that stores the
location information as well as basic height information in its RGBA
channel. For example, the red and green channels are the coverage
that altogether controls where the clouds tend to appear in the sky.
The blue channel can be used to control the peak height of the cloud
and the alpha channel can control the basic density of the cloud.
A 2D whether map with constant density will result in only dumb
clouds. From 12 we can see that real clouds tend to be rounded at
the bottom and will be more uy at the bottom and have more
dened shapes towards the top. In order to achieve these eects, we
will add some height-dependent functions that control the shape
and density.
3.2.2 Shape and Detail Noise. Uniform density could that weather
map generates is not enough. To add more details to the cloud, we
will use a 3D noise texture map to control the detailed density at
each point in the 3D space. The four channels of the texture will
store dierent frequency of noise. We will use Worley noise in this
project.
Combined with detailed noise, shape and density controls and
location parameter, we are now able to generate cloud-like volumes
with noise.
